ce:section.ce:para:
The core-shells design is another valuable technique for altering CD nanoparticles toward facilitating their biomedical application [66,67]. Numerous research has used metallic NPs like Ag to form a core–shell with CDs. The water dispersed-fluorescent carbon quantum dots (CDs) were synthesized using the microwave-assisted hydrothermal process in the closed system from the waste cotton linter as a new carbon source. This method provided an ultra-fast, more effective, economical, and easier synthesis for cancer-imaging applications compared to the other methods presented in the literature [68]. The surface-bound confinement of holes and electrons in CDs is the main factor causing their PL properties. Therefore, by trapping and entrapping electrons and holes, and reducing radiative recombination, the interaction of metallic ions with CDs causes PL to be quenched. Kong et al. [69] created the GQDs@Ag core–shell (
                        Fig. 2

                        ), which is employed for uric acid detection. Another study used the core–shell configuration of GQDs with Ag NPs to detect prostate-specific antigens (PSA). This product was created via electrostatic interactions between the carboxyl and hydroxyl groups of GQDs and the adsorbed Ag (NH3)2+ cation. Then Ag (NH3)2 gathered to form clusters, which later changed into Ag nanoparticles. Ag NPs that reduced the PL of GQDs were etched by H2O2, allowing the PL of the GQDs to recover. The observation of the PL intensity enhancement was made possible by raising the PSA concentration [70].
